description.text:
According to the original designer, sunnaem, this battle axe would have belonged to a viking king or a warrior in a special branch in the royal army
This was taken from the Google Sketchup Warehouse and converted to a printable file using Sketchup8.

Print two of these and glue them together with the smooth side in. You should be able to scale it larger or smaller as desired.
For that best effect, paint the part that wasn't already the right color. I printed in silver, which looked pretty realistic after some cleanup, and painted the handle brown.
I drilled a hole in the handle so it could be used as a key chain, but that's totally optional.

title: Raise Bed Height for Geeetech Aluminium i3

description.text:
Specific to this printer, there is not much of a gap between the bottom of the X axis and the Z axis coupler, so much so that if I am not careful the X axis bottoms out on the coupler and the motor overloads.

Since I have also upgraded the printer with the Z axis wobble eliminator and made my X axis free floating (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1431036) this gap is at the very extreme when homing the Z axis. Any adjustments I have made gives very little gap between the X axis and the coupler. I have tried.

So I made these blocks that go between the bearing and the aluminium base plate to raise the plate by 5 mm. This has solved my problem as I have an extra 5mm and the axis does not bottom out. Also now I can tension the bed springs properly, where before they were extended to the fullest resulting in some backlash on the X Y plane.

Printer:

Geeetech Full Metal Aluminum

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.2

Infill:

20%

Notes:

Need to print 4 of these as there are 4 bearings.

After printing, just unscrew the heated bed and move it aside. Unscrew the 4 screws for each bearing and insert the thingi in between the bearing and the plate and screw it back. Careful as the tolerance of the holes is very fine.

Make sure you align the object and the holes correctly.

Also you will need to add some padding to raise the Y axis endstop switch as well.

comments.text: Did you also create a small plate for lowering the belt-plate attachment. I think i'm experiencing a lot of wear on the idler pully bearing because of the fact the upper part of the y-belt is now shaped like a triangle because of the raised bed. (and possibly accuracy loss)
comments.author: Tommybear1979

comments.text: No I did not see the need. Belts are designed to be flexible. Nowhere does it say that a belt must be parallel. I am sure you have seen belts working in a triangle shape? If not let me assure you that they do. I have been using this mod ever since I posted the object and have not found any wear and tear nor any loss in accuracy especially since the plates are 5 mm in height. If you feel the need it is easy enough for you to make one and add it. I don't see the need.
comments.author: Tommybear1979

comments.text:
Well.. mathematically. (correct me if i'm wrong)
If we consider 'h' = 5mm as the height displacement.. and 'c' as the belt length between idlerpulley and buildplateconnection.
and 'y' as bed position.
I believe that c^2 = h^2 + y^2
y=(c^2 - h^2)^0.5
if you put that formula into excel you can see that the y-axis deviation from the wanted displacement c will vary from 0.1 to about 1.3mm
comments.author: bernbout

comments.text: Well mathematically speaking, you are using  Pythagoras theorem. Unfortunately you are assuming that c is going to be fixed. In this case, the only fixed length is y. Therefore h will increase by 5mm and c will also increase, because you have a belt adjuster to vary the tension and also the belt is not a rigid piece of steel, but a rubber belt which also stretches, while Y will ALWAYS remain constant because you have only increased h by 5 mm and not Y.
comments.author: Tommybear1979

comments.text:
c = the belt length between idlerpulley and the y-carriage mount (which in my case is 5mm elevated).
Therefore c is not constant, is varies by means of the stepper motor pulling in/out the belt..
Therefore in mid-y position the belt length c will be around 100mm. And at max y position the belt will have a length of about 5mm (right above/next-to idler pulley).

This is a set of obelisks to help make your scenes awesome. Seriously, this print has caused my players to gasp when they saw it. description.text:
Carefully hand modeled in C4D, this lovely box cradles your BlinkM controller in loving ABS.  You'll need a rubber band or something similarly classy to keep the lid on, though it fits pretty snuggly.  There is also no built-in means of attaching it to anything (like your TOM's z-stage assembly).  Finally, there's nothing really holding the board in place, so it can jiggle around.  Easy solutions abound. I settled for double sided mounting tape and a test cylinder. 
There are holes for DC power, 4-pin out to your RGB lights, and 4-pin in from Arduino or a LinkM.  The LinkM fits right in there.
I just wanted something to hold our blinkM in a happy box.  Said box could be improved in a million ways.

description.text:
As a present I recreated the heartgrenade from the album cover of a famous album by GD.

In the middle of the heartgrenade you can put something small, like money in my case. It's hold together by two neodym magnets.

If you wanna print it, print one half regularly and the other side flipped, so that both halves fit together.
I used four 25x8x2mm magnets. Before glueing them though, make sure that you got the polarities correct.
I used some cheap acrylic paint for the surface but i noticed that it's already lifting off. You might want to use a correct finish or something like clear vanish afterwards.
As you can see in the pictures, i also tried painting the magnets... Didn't really work obviously...

As a warning: I started 3d printing 3-4 weeks ago and this is the second thing i created. I'm not using a hot end fan, which kinda ruined the bridges in the cut outs... you can do that better probably.
Also, this was my first time trying to paint a 3d print.

All in all, many things went wrong, but it could have gone a lot worse. As a result it still turned out to be quite nice and I hope you gonna enjoy it too.

By the way: This also has a second use as i found out: It's a great fridge magnet!

description.text:
This started a a remix of Davross' DX4/5 battery cover but I can't seem to find that Thing now so I am crediting the DX8. The DX4/5 cover came "oh-so-close" to fitting on on the DX6i transmitter. I wanted to just make the minor changes required for a prefect fit for the DX6 and Davross had kindly supplied the 123D Design files. I downloaded 123D Design to make the changes and repost the files. Unfortunately 123D Design does not seem to let you go back and modify the sketches used to generate the 3D extrusions (sad face) so I gave up on modifying the files and recreated the part using Inventor. I did use the idea of building the support for the tabs in the model. Much better control of where the support material is placed than letting the printer decide. Will use this feature much in future designs.

The tabs (especially the middle one) will probably require some finish work to get a good "click" fit after removing the supports.

This is a Case made for my 4.3" HDMI Touchscreen project.
The unit encloses the electronics and LCD screen and has two mounting holes to allow it to be attached to something if needed. Has lots of vent holes, more to save plastic than to ventilate, as the unit doesn't really get hot. I've repeatedly tried to make this out of ABS and repeatedly failed with warping. So gave up and made it out of PLA instead. If you want more details of the 4.3" Touchscreen project, check out my project on sharedcircuits http://goo.gl/HnhTkx

When printing, try and put down extra glue on the corners to stop warping.
The Screen slots underneath a couple of overhangs at one end. These don't need support as they are short enough to not sag in either PLA or ABS. The mounting hex holes accept a M3 nut. Make sure you either use an End cap nut or don't over screw in the bolt, as it could go into the screen and crack it. I plan to stick down the other end with double sided sticky foam. For now I've used black tape, so that I can tinker with the electronics as needed. And lastly, Enjoy!

description.text: I took http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:12386 into tinkercad to create the 'raised' effect. At the current dimensions you can set the Z pause height to 6mm. When it stops it still has a layer or two to go so restart it and watch it for a bit with your finger over the 'change filament' option. Once it starts printing the inner wall press that button! Swap out with your blue with yellow for a cool M! The blue I used was a little on the light side but you get the idea. Edit: I have updated the file as the inset on the original was juuuust off (noticeable in larger M's) and it bothered me.

Default the base is 3mm so base your Z pause height off that and the scale (ie 300% scale = 9mm z pause). The Z pause doesn't stop exactly at the point where it switches to the inset so restart it and wait until you see it lay down the very first inset outline before initiating the 'change filament' pause. The couple of lines or so of blue are completely unnoticeable in the final print so don't worry about that.

This is a simple (But a bit messy) way to add some extra special sparkle to your printed objects.
All you need to do is sprinkle glitter onto a heated bed before printing with PLA - Clear PLA works great with all sorts of glitter colours but coloured PLA also works very well.
I have not tried ABS yet, but it should work just as well.
If you continue to sprinkle glitter as it builds (not too much) then your parts will have sparkle embedded all over them.
Have fun and brighten up your prints today!

It'll brighten up your prints and make someone's day special -
You can also embed other things like little plastic stars and other (thin) items, the PLA will just bond them into the first layer of the object. If you think of anything else to embed into prints, do let me know. Print a couple at opposite corners of your printer bed to give them time to cool between layers.

Pull apart the knife assembly with a pair of pliers and get the scissors out without bending them up. If you have a drill press handy you can drill out the rivets instead, but pliers work fine. Use the small spit ring to attach them to your keychain. Add the sheath and you're good to go.

My Victorinox Swiss Army Keychain Knife finally gave up (http://amzn.com/B00004YVB2) - lost the tweezers and the side plastic plates started coming off. I've bought a handful of these over the years and they last for a while. I find all I really need is the scissors - they can be a knife for opening boxes and such, too. So this sheath does the trick and it's a little smaller in your pocket. The walls could probably be a little bit thinner even, to cut a few more mm if you want to tinker with the 123D file.

I took a photo of the closed scissors. Turned it into an SVG using InkScape. Imported into 123D Design, scaled and extruded it to give it width. Built a simple solid block around it and subtracted the thick SVG profile. Printed a couple samples to check sizing, scaled the model in Repetier to get the fit right. Pushed those changes back into the 123D model, rebuilt the STL and posted.

These are made to fit nicely on my spools for use with a Hatchbox spool holder (although it should fit any spool holder with a 25mm rod diameter). I don't know if it's just my printer or what, but the similar ones from another file, set to 25mm exactly, did not fit on my spool rod... so I made these 25.5mm and they fit perfectly! I printed mine using a 0.3mm nozzle at a 0.2mm and it worked fine.

Printer:

Geeetech i3 Pro C

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.2

Infill:

at least 30%

Notes:

[email protected] w/ 0.3mm nozzle @ 0.2mm resolution. I did print mine with a brim (not a full raft). I'm not sure it was necessary, but I was worried about the thinner parts moving early in the print. Also, 30% infill is the minimum you should use! My hub-adapter designs are thinner than the originals, so they need plenty of rigidity in those arms! Even though they're thinner, I have no issues at all, I've been using them for two days now, printing almost non-stop day & night, and of the four in use none of them are even slightly worked out of place.

just make sure there is no flanging at the edges, of the inner-ring especially! They should spin freely on the spool rod with pretty much no resistance. If they don't spin freely you should work them a bit with an exacto (for edges) and a finger wrapped in sand-paper (for the inner-surface). Mine required nothing more than cleanly removing the brim.
I take no credit whatsoever! I just tweaked the design to accommodate my Hatchbox dual spool holder!
